INSERT INTO `TEAM` (`ID`, `Name`, `Email`, `Position`, `Description`, `Social_Media`, `Publications`, `Presentations`, `Image`) VALUES
(1, 'Prof David Stifter', 'david.stifter@mu.ie', 'PI', 'Current Research Interests: Language variation and change in Old Irish, comparative Celtic linguistics (esp. Old Irish and Continental Celtic), language contact in the ancient world and on the early medieval British Isles.  Professor David Stifter is Professor of Old Irish at Maynooth University Department of Early Irish since 2011. He received an ERC Consolidator Grant for the project \'Chronologicon Hibernicum - A Probabilistic Chronological Framework for Dating Early Irish Language Developments and Literature\' (Horizon2020 Grant Agreement no. 647351) in 2015. He studied Latin, Russian and Indo-European linguistics at the University of  Vienna, and received his Mag. Phil. in 1998 for a thesis on the Old Irish influence on the Latin of the Nauigatio Sancti Brendani Abbatis. As part of his studies, he spent the year 1995/6 at Maynooth University studying Old and Middle Irish with Prof. Kim McCone. In 2003 he was awarded his PhD for a thesis on the Didactics of Old Irish.  From 2000–2008 David Stifter was contract assistant at the Department of Linguistics at the University of Vienna. During this time, he played a major role in establishing and developing the Celtic studies programme at the University. He is a founding member and secretary of the Societas Celtologica Europaea (European Association of Celtic Studies scholars)  From 2006, he directed and worked on three different research projects:  a dictionary of the Old Irish glosses in the Milan manuscript Ambr. C301 infr. (http://www.univie.ac.at/indogermanistik/milan_glosses.htm) Lexicon Leponticum - an interactive etymological dictionary plus edition of texts of Lepontic (http://www.univie.ac.at/lexlep/wiki/Main_Page) a study of the linguistic remains of Celtic in Austria (http://www.univie.ac.at/austria-celtica/personalnames/) Prof. Stifter is currently Principal Investigator in the ERC-funded project Chronologicon Hibernicum - A Probabilistic Chronological Framework for Dating Early Irish Language Developments and Literature\' (https://www.maynoothuniversity.ie/chronhib Professor Stifter has published widely on the Old and Middle Irish language and literature, and on the Continental Celtic languages (Celtiberian, Gaulish and Lepontic). His introductory handbook Sengoídelc. Old Irish for Beginners (Syracuse University Press 2006) has been adopted for teaching Old Irish in universities world-wide and was awarded the 2006 Michael J. Durkan Prize for Books on Language and Culture of the American Conference for Irish Studies.  He is founder and editor of the interdisciplinary Celtic-studies journal Keltische Forschungen (Vienna 2006–).  He co-edited several volumes in Celtic and Indo-European linguistics, among them the four-volume collection The Celtic World. Critical Concepts in Historical Studies (Routledge 2007).', '', '', '‘Chronologicon Hibernicum’ (Imbolc, Baile Bhúirne, 6 February 2016)  ‘The British Connections of the Poems of Blathmac’ (30th Irish Conference of Medi­eval­ists, Maynooth University, 30 June–2 July 2016, 1 July 2016).  with Fangzhe Qiu and Elliott Lash, ‘Chronologicon Hibernicum’ (Tionól of the School of Celtic Studies, Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies, 17–19 November 2016, 17 November 2016).  ‘How to conceptualise numbers in Early Irish… and other languages’, Research Seminar of the Department for Mathematics and Statistics, Maynooth University, 15 February 2017.  ‘The Celtic Epigraphic Evidence’ (Runic Inscriptions and the Early History of the Germanic Languages, University of Southern Denmark Odense, 14 March 2017).  ‘Words words words’ (31st Irish Conference of Medievalists, Maynooth University, 29 June–1 July 2017, 29 June 2017).  ‘What Can We Say about a Word?’ (plenary paper at the 2nd Symposium of the Societas Celtologica Europaea, Bangor University/Wales, 31 July–2 August 2017, 1 August 2017).  ‘Ancient Celtic Epigraphy and its Interface with Classical Epigraphy’ (XVth Inter­national Congress of Greek and Latin Epigraphy, Universität Wien, 25–30 August 2017).  ‘The state of Celtic Studies in the German-speaking countries’ (17th International Con­ference in Irish-German Studies. Irish-German Relations 2017: Between Böll and Bre­xit, Centre for German-Irish Studies, University of Limerick, 14–16 September 2017, 16 September 2017).  ‘Chronologicon Hibernicum – Towards a Methodology of Dating Early Irish Language Developments’ (The Dating of Old Norse and Celtic Texts, University of Oslo, 22–23 March 2018, 22 March 2018).  ‘Celtic Maritime Vocabulary’ (When Archaeology meets linguistics and genetics, 3–4 May 2018, Universiteit Göteborg, 4 May 2018).‘Old Irish 2.0: Tapping tech, stats (and old-fashioned human brain power) to date an­cient languages’ (Maynooth University Summer Soirée, Maynooth, 16 June 2018)with Fangzhe Qiu and Elliott Lash, ‘Introduction to Chronologicon Hibernicum’ (10th Celtic Linguistics Conference, Maynooth University, 4–5 September 2018, 4 September 2018).‘Old Irish Etymology through the Ages’ (Annual Meeting of the Henry Sweet Society for the History of Linguistic Ideas, Maynooth University, 5–8 September 2018, 6 September 2018).‘Top-notch. Ogam and vernacular Irish literacy in Late Antiquity and the very early Middle Ages’ (Latinization in the north-western provinces: language death and surviv­al in the Roman and post-Roman world. Workshop, All Souls College, Oxford, 17–18 September 2018, 18 September 2018).with Angelina Lavelle, ‘Alliterate by Number’ (Tionól of the School of Celtic Studies, Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies, 2–3 November 2018, 2 November 2018).‘Tria Dliged do Dána ‘By the Rules of your Art’ – DisARTiculating the ARTsy-FARTsy ARTistry of Poetry of Fil and grian Glinne Aí’ (Research Seminar, Queen’s University Belfast, 30 November 2018).‘The Language of Cín Dromma Snechtai’, (‘A little remnant of the work of the ancients’. 23 N 10: the Book of Ballycummin. Conference, Royal Irish Academy, Dublin, 7-8 March 2019, 8 March 2019).‘Insular Celtic and Ogham script’, (Lenguas y escrituras paleoeuropeas: retos y perspectivas de estudio. Coloquio internacional (AELAW), Escuela Espanola de Historia y Arqueología, Rome, 13-15 March 2019, 14 March 2019).‘When is Variation a Dialect? The Case of Old Irish’, O’Donnell Lecture 2019, Oxford University, 10 May 2019.‘The riddles of Fil and griän Glinne Aí’ (masterclass at the Oxford-Cambridge Celtic Colloquium 2019, Oxford University, 11 May 2019).‘The gravyty of dark matter – solving the riddles of Fil and grian Glinne Aí’ (‘To frighten off the rude and ignorant’? Intentional obscuritas in Irish and Welsh literature (650–1650), Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies, 24-25 May 2019, 25 May 2019).together with Marco Aquino-López, ‘Statistical methods in the Old Irish language: A methods point of view of the ChronHib project’ (Statistics in Historical Corpus Lingui­stics, ChronHib workshop, Maynooth University, 4-5 October 2019, 4 October 2019).‘The stars look very different today’ (Samhain agus Science, Dublin Institute for Ad­vanced Studies, 30 October 2019).‘The stars look very different today’ (Early Irish Research Seminar, Maynooth University, 21 November 2019).‘Pre-Roman Epigraphic Cultures: Gaulish and Italo-Celtic (and Ogam)’ International Training  School. The Epigraphic Text. Text, Theory, Practice. Computerization and Digitization, Alteritas, Verona, 7-11 September 2020, 8 September 2020.‘The Dark Sides of the Moon and Every Other Heavenly Thing under the Sun in Medieval Irish Tradition’ (Mahindra Humanities Center Medieval Studies Seminar, Harvard University, 23 October 2020).‘Vocative for Nominative’ (Research Seminar of the Institute of Linguistic Research, Russian Academy of Sciences, St Petersburg, 8 December 2020).‘Presentation: Corpus PalaeoHibernicum’, Representing Texts: from Material to Digital (workshop for AHRC-IRC Digital Humanities Networking grant ‘A Digital Framework for the Medieval Gaelic World’, 21-22 January 2021, 22 January 2021).‘The Old Irish healing charms in the Stowe Missal and the protective spell in the Karls­ruhe book cover’ (Medicine in the Medieval North Atlantic World, Maynooth University, 13-15 May 2021, 14 May 2021).together with Bernhard Bauer, Elliott Lash, Fangzhe Qiu, Nora White, ‘Corpus PalaeoHibernicum - a deeply annotated lexicographic database of Early Irish’, (11th International Conference on Historical Lexicography and Lexicology, La Rioja, June 2021).', ''),
(2, 'Dr Bernhard Bauer', 'bernhard.w.bauer@gmail.com', 'Postdoctoral Researcher', 'I hold a PhD in Indo-European Linguistics from the University of Vienna for my dissertation \"Intra-Celtic Loanwords\". I am a PostDoc within the Chronologicon Hibernicum. Since my Master’s thesis in Celtic Studies on the Old Breton glosses, vernacular Celtic glosses and their Latin counterparts have a played a central role in my research, e.g., while working on the “Dictionary of the Old Irish Priscian glosses” and my postdoctoral project “Languages in Exchange: Ireland and her Neighbours”. I have published on different aspects of the Celtic glossing tradition on Priscian, Bede and Orose using traditional methodology and methods of the digital humanities.', 'https://twitter.com/Bernhard_Baver; https://github.com/BernBa; https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2881-0972; https://www.linkedin.com/in/bernhard-bauer-736520204/', 'Bauer 2015', '‘(Semi) Automatised transcription of medieval manuscripts: Optical Character Recognition & Handwritten Text Recognition’ (Invited speaker) presented at Workshop: Representing Texts: From Material to Digital, Maynooth University, Ire­land, January 22, 2021.\r\n\r\n‘Corpus PalaeoHibernicum’ presented at Workshop: Representing Texts: From Material to Digital, Maynooth University, Ire­land, January 22, 2021. Together with David Stifter, Fangzhe Qiu, Elliott Lash and Godstime Osarobo.\r\n\r\n‘Distant Reading of Glossed Corpora: Stylometry and Network Analysis’ (Invited speaker) presented at Workshop: Glossing in Celtic Contexts, Virginia Tech, Blacksburg, VA, USA, September 18, 2020.\r\n\r\n‘ChronHib, CorPH and the Corphusator: building an Early Irish corpus’ (Invited speaker) Invited lecture at Insight, SFI Research Centre for Data Analytics, NUI Galway, Ireland, February 5, 2020.\r\n\r\n‘Interpreting Early Medieval Glosses as scholarly and intellectual networks’ (Invited speaker) presented at Workshop: Literary, Historical, and Cultural Networks at Maynooth University, Ire­land, January 14, 2020.\r\n\r\n‘Translating glosses and ideas in Irish Priscian manuscripts’ presented at Tionól of the School for Celtic Studies at the Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies, Ireland, November 15, 2019. Together with Victoria Krivoshchekova.\r\n\r\n‘How to tag an Old Irish word’ presented at The XVIth International Congress of Celtic Studies, Bangor University, Wales, July 22, 2019.\r\n\r\n‘‘Are you suggesting that glosses migrate?’ – The ‘Celtic’ Orosius Glosses’ presented at Glossing from a comparative perspective, Philipps ­Universität Marburg, Germany, June 6, 2019.\r\n\r\n‘Of seagulls and unmarried men: Strata in the Old Irish Priscian glosses’ presented at XI Congreso Internacional de Lingüística de Corpus – XI International Conference on Corpus Linguistics, València, Spain, May 15, 2019.\r\n\r\n‘Introducing Chronologicon Hibernicum’ presented at EuroMED 2018, Nicosia, Cyprus, November 2, 2018.\r\n\r\n‘Observations on the date of Story of the abbot and the devil’ presented at 30th Irish Conference for Medievalists, Maynooth, Ireland, July 1, 2016.', ''),
(3, 'Dr Fangzhe Qiu', 'fangzhe.qiu@ucd.ie', 'Postdoctoral Researcher', 'Fangzhe worked at the ChronHib project from September 2015 to December 2019. He was an O’Donovan postdoctoral Scholar at the School of Celtic Studies, Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies before joining the team. Fangzhe got his MPhil. in Celtic Studies from Oxford University in 2011, and PhD in Early and Medieval Irish from University College Cork in 2015. Fangzhe now works as a lecturer in Early Irish and Celtic Studies in University College Dublin. His research interests include Early Irish language, annalistic texts, early Irish law and historical linguistics.', 'https://people.ucd.ie/fangzhe.qiu;https://orcid.org/0000-0002-7167-9001;https://www.linkedin.com/in/fangzhe-dimurjan-qiu-4755882b/', '', '‘The language of the Annals of Ulster - then and now’, presented at the Ó Cléirigh Seminar, UCD, 22 Nov 2019.\r\n‘Revisiting the Nordic names in pre-12th century Irish annals’, presented at the annual Tionól, Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies, 14 Nov 2019.\r\n‘What is in a name? A guided tour to medieval Irish names’, presented at the Maynooth University Research Week Ignite Presentation Competition, 22 Oct 2019 (winner of 1st prize).\r\n‘The distribution of passive endings -a(i)r vs. -tha(i)r in Old Irish’, presented at the XVIth International Congress of Celtic Studies, Bangor, 22 Jul 2019.\r\n‘Strategies in tracing linguistic variation in the Corpus of Old Irish texts’, presented at the XI International Conference on Corpus Linguistics, Valencia, 17 May 2019.\r\n‘Chronologicon Hibernicum: frámaíocht dhóchúlaíoch chun dátú a dhéanamh ar fhorbairtí i dteanga na Sean-Ghaeilge’, presented at the Fiftieth Léachtaí Cholm Cille, Maynooth, 27 Apr 2019.\r\n‘When were the 6th- and 7th- century entries in the Annals of Ulster written? A quantitative approach’, presented at the Workshop on Irish Annals, 22 Sep 2017.\r\n‘When were the 6th- and 7th- century entries in the Annals of Ulster written? A quantitative approach’, presented at the 2nd European Symposium of Celtic Studies, Bangor, 1 Aug 2017.\r\n‘Auë ‘descendant’ and its descendants’, presented at the Irish Conference of Medievalists, Maynooth, 3 Jul 2017.\r\n(With D. Stifter and E. Lash) ‘Chronologicon Hibernicum (ChronHib)’, presented at the annual Tionól, 17 Nov 2016.\r\n‘Verses in ‘The Chronicle of Ireland’? some textual and linguistic evidence’, presented at the Eleanor Knott Memorial Conference, TCD, 28 Apr 2016.', ''),
